node.text: Like many people I remember the first time I stood in Yosemite National Park, at this particular spot, like it was yesterday. It was a sunny day and we had driven through the night, both of us utterly exhausted. I’d seen so many photos, I thought I knew what to expect and in some ways it did seem familiar, but after standing here for an hour I still couldn’t believe what I was seeing. That feeling of magnitude and grandeur has never waned in all my visits since. It makes me feel like a kid again, where everything you experience is new and exciting.

Whenever I’m down in California, I make it a priority to spend some time in the Eastern Sierras... Haven’t missed it yet, and don’t plan to either. The weather is always amazing, America’s tallest peak is just out of frame to the right, and there’s endless fun things to do. I’ve hiked, climbed, camped, and traversed a few 4x4 trails in this area. It’s an outdoor lover’s paradise and on mornings like this, a photographers dream come true as well 💫 @eddiebauer #LiveYourAdventure #EBContributor

El Capitan in motion... My road trip is coming to an end as all great things tend to do. Now the fun part begins, sifting through the thousands of photos and videos to find the best of the best and to tell the story. In the mean time, enjoy the first time lapse I’ve ever made, on a particularly beautiful day in Yosemite National Park 💫
A collection of photos from a particularly stunning sunset a few days back. Taken from side of a highway in the middle of nowhere in California 💫

In the depths of the Pacific Northwest, there are places where the rain never stops. Rainforests, rivers, waterfalls... The rhythmic dripping hypnotizing those who listen long enough.... When I’m outside tuning in to the songs of the forest, I trust @eddiebauer to keep me dry. #LiveYourAdventure #EBContributor
Hot spring season is finally here ✨ If you zoom in you’ll see me smiling ear to ear... Happy to be traveling and soaking in one of my favorite pools again
23 miles from the nearest road with too many blueberries and black bears to count... This was our home away from home for a few nights
Morning pastels over Mount Rainier, taken from one of my favorite summit trips of the summer; Mount Daniel ✨

I’ve traversed the mountains here in the Northwest, searching far and wide for little pieces of paradise. Some spots have taken days and many miles to get to, other places are just around the corner on a popular trail... @eddiebauer and their First Ascent line of outerwear has given me more confidence than ever before to venture beyond what I thought was possible for myself. Any weather condition, any time of year... I don’t hesitate, I just grab my gear and hit the trail #LiveYourAdventure #EBContributor
Early morning hues in the North Cascades 💫
Taking a walk on the wild side 🌲
A ripper of a sunset from April of this year... Somehow this one stayed in the camera roll until I stumbled upon it yesterday
Layers upon layers of beautiful Cascadian rock. From one of the longest and sendiest weeks of summer... I think I managed 60 miles on three different trips.

Hello everyone... It’s been a little while, a month to be exact. Back in late September I partially tore my right achilles and developed tendinitis in both. Recovery has been extremely painful and tediously slow but for the most part I’m ready to hike again (YAY!) That injury, along with a few other important moments, caused me to step back from social media altogether and really think about what I’m doing here and why I’m doing it. For much of the last year I’ve wanted to do more; tell a more complete story, give back to my community both here in Seattle and online, and use my presence to share important messages... But I couldn’t figure out how. This time away has given me the space to move forward with what I want to be doing. While it may not be obvious at the start, and I’m purposely being ambiguous, it’s my hope that everything will come into light over the next few months. I’m energized and extremely excited for what I’m doing and I can’t wait to bring y’all along. Anyways... if you’ve made it this far, thanks for coming to my TED talk! I’m leaving for a road trip next week and I hope to see some of you beautiful people on my travels 😘
A morning so still and perfect, it was hard to know when dreams from the night before ended and reality began ✨🍂

A morning to remember... All year long, I envision a few moments like this for Autumn; golden larch trees lit up by the brilliant morning sun. This one stands out exceptionally well as it was most likely, my last big hike for the year. I came away from this 30 mile journey with tendinitis in both of my achilles... The miles of trail this year, of which there were many, finally caught up to me. So I’ve been resting, planning my winter, and savoring the moments I had in the mountains this year. I’ll be back on the trails stronger than ever in no time but for now... Enjoy a highlight from my even shorter and sweeter Autumn.
Don’t be afraid to be a little different from the rest 🌲🍁
The Hunt for Orange October

In my early twenties I would count down the days of summer, waiting for the snow to fly... At the time I was a ski-bum of sorts, working seasonal jobs at my local ski resorts. Nowadays it’s reversed and I’m counting down the days of winter, waiting for the meadows to thaw and flowers to bloom in the high country. On this recent trip something clicked and my mind set changed... The snow covered mountains and crystal clear air set in motion an eagerness to enjoy each season as it happens, even if that means snow in September. We can’t control a lot of things in life but we can control our attitude towards them. So here’s me, welcoming Winter with open arms... Even if the calendar and the golden foliage tell me it’s Autumn.

One of my last sunrises from this summer... After the orange hues faded away I found a patch of heather to sprawl out in, napping in the early morning warmth. Those sublime mornings are in the past, for now, as the leaves and snowflakes fall...
Perhaps the coldest water we’ve ever swam in... Deep in the Idaho backcountry with no one around for miles and miles

Deep in the forest, where the trail tests you and tries with all its might to break you, is where you find out just how hard you’re willing to push yourself.... This photo is from day one of three of a trip that beat us down in every way imaginable
Summer’s gone. With the flip of a switch, Autumn has arrived. These summit views are going to be harder to come by, but all the more rewarding... Bring it on 🤟🏼

I’m not entirely sure what I was expecting as we set off to spend a week hiking in Idaho but it certainly wasn’t this... Dozens of alpine lakes, rugged and steep off trail travel, and jagged peaks as far as our eyes could see. It’s still the Wild West out there, true untamed wilderness... I’m officially hooked and we’re already planning our next trip to this outdoor wonderland
Dear Washington... You’re beautiful beyond words ✨
